'''Kylie Rae Harris''' (May 15, 1989 {{ndash}} September 4, 2019) was an American singer-songwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/kylie-rae-harris-fashion-playlist/|title=Texas Artist Kylie Rae Harris Shares Festival Fashion Looks and Summer-Ready Playlist [Exclusive]|last=Sawyer|first=Bobbie Jean|date=June 12, 2019|website=Wide Open Country|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dallasobserver.com/music/kylie-rae-harris-on-singing-with-zane-williams-and-her-excellent-new-ep-7053584|title=Kylie Rae Harris on Singing with Zane Williams and Her (Excellent) New EP|last=Dearmore|first=Kelly|date=September 20, 2013|website=[[Dallas Observer]]|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guitargirlmag.com/news/music-news/singer-songwriter-kylie-rae-harris-looks-deeper-at-lessons-learned/|title=Singer-Songwriter Kylie Rae Harris Looks Deeper at Lessons Learned|date=March 26, 2019|website=Guitar Girl Magazine|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centraltrack.com/song-of-the-day-kylie-rae-harris-big-ol-heartache/|title=Song of the Day: Kylie Rae Harris – "Big Ol' Heartache."|last=Graves|first=Cory|date=February 4, 2019|website=Central Track|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> She was born in [[Wylie, Texas]].

== Career ==
At age twelve, Harris was enrolled in a vocal camp and began crafting her own songs and playing guitar. By the time she graduated from high school, Harris earned a music scholarship and a welding scholarship, but took neither and decided to press on with her musical career. She was one of the featured artists in ''[[Troubadour, TX]]'', a television show documenting her rising career as a Texas country singer-songwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://popculture.com/country-music/2019/09/05/kylie-rae-harris-country-singer-reveals-was-approached-abc-reality-show/|title=Country Singer Kylie Rae Harris Reveals She Was Approached for ABC Reality Show|website=Country Music}}</ref>

On July 1, 2010, Harris released her debut album titled ''All the Right Reasons'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Kylie-Rae-Harris-All-The-Right-Reasons/release/13373990|title=Kylie Rae Harris – All The Right Reasons|date=2010 |publisher=discogs}}</ref> followed by an EP in 2013 titled ''Taking It Back''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Kylie-Rae-Harris-Taking-It-Back/release/13373975|title=Kylie Rae Harris – Taking It Back|date=2013 |publisher=discogs}}</ref>

In 2013, Harris began working on material for a second full-length album and toured with fellow ''Troubadour, TX'' star [[Zane Williams]] throughout the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.earnthenecklace.com/kylie-rae-harris-wiki/|title=Who Is Kylie Rae Harris: Wiki and Facts About the Deceased Country Singer|last=John|first=Caroline |date=September 6, 2019|website=Earn The Necklace|access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Then in March 2019, she released a new self titled EP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dallasobserver.com/music/wylies-kylie-rae-harris-has-a-new-self-titled-ep-out-11627825|title=Kylie Rae Harris Looks Back and Moves Forward on Her New EP|last=Dearmore|first=Kelly|date=March 29, 2019|website=[[Dallas Observer]]|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>

== Death ==
Harris died on September 4, 2019, when her car collided with another near [[Taos, New Mexico]]. She was 30 years old<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.taosnews.com/stories/sheriff-speed-likely-contributed-to-crash-that-killed-taos-high-teen-texas-singer,59343 |title=Sheriff: Speed likely contributed to crash that killed Taos High teen, Texas singer |last=Matlock |first=Staci |date=September 5, 2019 |work=[[Taos News]] |access-date=September 7, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name="cnn._Coun">{{Cite web|title=Country singer Kylie Rae Harris dies in car accident|last=Gonzalez|first=Sandra|website=[[CNN]]|date=September 5, 2019| access-date=September 5, 2019|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/05/entertainment/kylie-rae-harris-country-singer-dead-trnd/index.html}}</ref> and is survived by her daughter.<ref name="bill_Kyli">{{Cite magazine|title=Kylie Rae Harris Dead: Country Singer Dies In Car Accident|last=Reuter |first=Annie|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=September 5, 2019|access-date=September 5, 2019|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8529184/kylie-rae-harris-dies-country-singer-dead-car-accident}}</ref> A subsequent investigation, completed in December 2019, revealed she had been driving up to {{convert|102|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} ({{convert|95|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} when the crash occurred), confirmed by her vehicle's computer, and had a blood alcohol level three times the legal limit. Harris clipped the rear end of a vehicle in the right lane, swerved into oncoming traffic,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/country-singer-kylie-rae-harris-was-drunk-speeding-deadly-new-n1096906|title=Country singer Kylie Rae Harris was drunk, speeding at over 100 mph before deadly crash|website=[[NBC News]]|date=December 6, 2019 |language=en|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/country-singer-kylie-rae-harris-drunk-speeding-fatal-crash-police|title=Country singer Kylie Rae Harris' alcohol level was 3 times legal limit, driving 102 mph at time of crash|website=Fox News|language=en|access-date=December 6, 2019|date=December 6, 2019}}</ref> and hit another car head-on.  The driver of the other car, 16-year-old Taos High School student Maria Elena Cruz, was also killed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Country singer Kylie Rae Harris caused "senseless" crash that killed her and teen, sheriff says |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/kylie-rae-harris-crash-deadly-crash-cause-by-country-singer-taos-county-sheriff-says/ |accessdate=September 9, 2019 |website=[[CBS News]] |date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> Cruz's father, Deputy Chief Pedro Cruz of the San Cristobal Fire District, responded to the call not knowing his daughter had been involved in the accident.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Stimson |first=Brie |date=2019-09-08 |title=Kylie Rae Harris crash a shock for NM fire chief; learns his 16-year-old daughter also died |url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/emt-responds-to-country-singers-fatal-crash-unaware-his-16-year-old-daughter-also-killed |access-date=2023-08-25 |website=Fox News |language=en-US}}</ref>

Harris had a drunk driving conviction from 2017. As part of her conviction, she was ordered to have an [[ignition interlock device]] installed in her car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/kylie-rae-harris-dead-crash-speeding-sheriff|title=Kylie Rae Harris was driving 102 mph at time of fatal crash, authorities say|last=Sager|first=Jessica|date=September 23, 2019|website=[[Fox News]]|language=en-US|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>{{Relevance inline|date=December 2019}}

